GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 824
Short Title: Expand Treatment Access/Opioid Use Disorder. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives White and Huneycutt (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Insurance, if favorable, Finance, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of
the House
April 9, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO EXPAND ACCESS TO TREATMENT FOR OPIOID OVERDOSE AND OPIOID
3 USE DISORDER BY UPDATING HEALTH BENEFIT PLAN COVERAGE OF, AND
4 REIMBURSEMENT FOR, OVERDOSE AND SUBSTANCE USE DISORDER
5 MEDICATIONS AND TO MAKE TECHNICAL AND CONFORMING CHANGES TO
6 UPDATE THE GENERAL STATUTES THAT RELATE TO MENTAL HEALTH
7 COVERAGE UNDER HEALTH BENEFIT PLANS.
8 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
9
10 PART I. CREATE PARITY FOR COVERAGE UNDER A HEALTH BENEFIT PLAN
11 APPLICABLE TO PHARMACIES AND PHARMACISTS
12
13 REQUIRE CERTAIN PHARMACY SERVICES TO BE COVERED UNDER A HEALTH
14 BENEFIT PLAN
15 SECTION 1.1.(a) Article 3 of Chapter 58 of the General Statutes is amended by
16 adding a new section to read:
17 "§ 58-3-241. Healthcare services provided by pharmacists.
18 (a) The following definitions apply in this section:
19 (1) Healthcare services. – Any of the following health or medical procedures or
20 services rendered by a healthcare provider:
21 a. Testing, assessment, and management of a health condition, illness,
22 injury, or disease. This includes testing, diagnosis, or treatment
23 rendered by a pharmacist acting within the pharmacist's scope of
24 practice.
25 b. Dispensing of drugs, medical devices, medical appliances, or medical
26 goods for the treatment of a health condition, illness, injury, or disease.
27 c. Administration of a vaccine or medication, including long-term
28 injectables such as buprenorphine.
29 (2) Pharmacist. – An individual licensed to practice pharmacy under Article 4A
30 of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes or the relevant laws of another state.
31 (b) A health benefit plan offered by an insurer in this State shall cover healthcare services
32 provided by a pharmacist if all of the following conditions are met:
33 (1) The service or procedure was performed within the pharmacist's licensed
34 lawful scope of practice.
*H824-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The health benefit plan would have covered the service if the service or
2 procedure had been performed by another healthcare provider.
3 (c) The participation of a pharmacy in a drug benefit provider network of a health benefit
4 plan shall not satisfy any requirement that insurers offering health benefit plans include
5 pharmacists in medical benefit provider networks."
6 SECTION 1.1.(b) This section is effective October 1, 2025, and applies to insurance
7 contracts issued, amended, or renewed on or after that date.
8
9 ACCEPT HEALTHCARE FACILITY CREDENTIALING FOR PHARMACISTS
10 EMPLOYED BY THE FACILITY
11 SECTION 1.2.(a) G.S. 58-3-230 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
12 "(d) Insurers that delegate credentialing agreements or requirements for pharmacists
13 licensed under Article 4A of Chapter 90 of the General Statutes or the relevant laws of another
14 state to a contracted healthcare facility shall accept the credentialing for all pharmacists employed
15 by, or contracted with, those healthcare facilities."
16 SECTION 1.2.(b) This section is effective October 1, 2025, and applies to insurance
17 contracts issued, amended, or renewed on or after that date.
18
19 PART II. ENHANCE COVERAGE OF PRESCRIPTION DRUGS FOR OPIOID
20 DISORDER AND OPIOID OVERDOSE UNDER HEALTH BENEFIT PLANS
21 SECTION 2.1. G.S. 58-3-220 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
22 "(k) Select Prescription Drugs. – Insurers offering a health benefit plan shall provide
23 coverage of all prescription drugs approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration
24 for the treatment of opioid disorder and opioid overdose. If an insurer maintains one or more
25 closed formularies, then all prescription drugs requiring coverage under this section shall be
26 included on those formularies. The following shall apply to prescription drugs for which coverage
27 is required under this subsection:
28 (1) The prescription drug shall not be subject to prior authorization as a condition
29 of coverage.
30 (2) Pharmacies dispensing the prescription drug shall be reimbursed at the most
31 recent National Average Drug Acquisition Cost price plus a dispensing fee. If
32 the prescription drug dispensed is not available on the most recent National
33 Average Drug Acquisition Cost price list, then the most recent Wholesale
34 Acquisition Cost price plus a dispensing fee shall be used to reimburse
35 pharmacies for dispensing the prescription drug."
36 SECTION 2.2. This Part is effective October 1, 2025, and applies to insurance
37 contracts issued, amended, or renewed on or after that date.
38
39 PART III. CONFORM TO FEDERAL LAW AND MAKE OTHER TECHNICAL
40 CHANGES TO UPDATE THE GENERAL STATUTES THAT RELATE TO MENTAL
41 HEALTH COVERAGE UNDER HEALTH BENEFIT PLANS
42 SECTION 3.1.(a) Subsections (b), (c), (d), and (j) of G.S. 58-3-220 are repealed.
43 SECTION 3.1.(b) Subsection (h) of G.S. 58-3-220 is recodified as subsection (a1)
44 of G.S. 58-3-220.
45 SECTION 3.2. G.S. 58-3-220, as amended by Part II and Section 3.1 of this act,
46 reads as rewritten:
47 "§ 58-3-220. Mental illness health benefits coverage.
48 (a) Mental Health Equity Requirement. – Except as provided in subsection (b), an insurer
49 shall provide in each group health benefit plan benefits for All health benefit plans shall provide
50 coverage for the necessary care and treatment of mental illnesses health conditions that are no
51 less favorable than benefits for the necessary care and treatment of physical illness generally,
